# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: caffeine
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was first reported by Henri Victor Regnault in 1840.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Industrially, it is usually produced in a two-step process from vinyl chloride.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction is catalyzed by a variety of Lewis acids, mainly aluminium chloride, iron(III) chloride, or zinc chloride.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This reaction proceeds at 80%–90% yield, and the hydrogen chloride byproduct can be recycled to the first step in the process.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The major side-product is the related compound 1,1,2-trichloroethane, from which the 1,1,1-trichloroethane can be separated by distillation.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is sold with stabilizers because it is unstable with respect to dehydrochlorination and attacks some metals.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Stabilizers comprise up to 8% of the formulation, including acid scavengers (epoxides, amines) and complexants.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] One discontinued product contained only 1,4-dioxane (2%±1%), while another chemical supplier included 2.5% 1,4-dioxane, 0.47% 1,2-butylene oxide, and 0.35% nitromethane as stabilizers.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is an excellent solvent for many organic compounds and one of the least toxic of the chlorinated hydrocarbons.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It is generally considered non-polar, but owing to the good polarizability of the chlorine atoms, it is a superior solvent for organic compounds that do not dissolve well in hydrocarbons such as hexane.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Prior to the Montreal Protocol, it was widely used for cleaning metal parts and circuit boards, as a photoresist solvent in the electronics industry, as an aerosol propellant, as a cutting fluid additive, and as a solvent for inks, paints, adhesives, and other coatings.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used to dry-clean leather and suede.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Use in dry-cleaning remained until the 1980s.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was used as an insecticidal fumigant.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also the standard cleaner for photographic film.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Other commonly available solvents damage emulsion and base (acetone will dissolve triacetate base on most films), and thus are not suitable for this application.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The standard replacement, Forane 141 is much less effective, and tends to leave a residue.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was also used as a thinner in correction fluid products such as liquid paper.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Many of its applications previously used carbon tetrachloride (which was banned in US consumer products in 1970).
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In turn, 1,1,1-trichloroethane itself is now being replaced by other solvents in the laboratory.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Phase-out of 1,1,1-Trichloroethane due to ozone depletion lead to a resurgence of the use of trichloroethylene in metal degreasing.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Methyl chloroform was also used as a veterinary anthelmintic.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane was one of the volatile organochlorides that have been tried as alternatives to chloroform in anaesthesia.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In the 1880s, it was found to be a safe and strong substitute for chloroform but its production was too expensive and difficult for the era.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] In 1880, 1,1,1-trichloroethane was suggested as an anaesthetic.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] It was first referred to as methyl-chloroform in the same year.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] At the time, the narcotic effects of chloral hydrate were owed to a hypothetical metabolic pathway to chloroform in "alkaline blood".
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Trichloroethane was studied for its structural similarity to chloral and potential anaesthetic effects.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] However, trichloroethane did not exhibit any conversion to chloroform in laboratory experiments.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The 1,1,2-Trichloroethane (vinyl trichloride) isomer, which lacked a trichloromethyl group, exhibited anaesthetic effects even stronger than the 1,1,1 isomer.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The International Agency for Research on Cancer places 1,1,1-trichloroethane in Group 2A as a probable carcinogen.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] 1,1,1-Trichloroethane is a fairly potent greenhouse gas with a 100-year global warming potential of 169 relative to carbon dioxide.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] This is nonetheless less than a tenth that of carbon tetrachloride — which it replaced as a solvent — due to its relatively short atmospheric lifetime of about 5 years.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] The Montreal Protocol targeted 1,1,1-trichloroethane as a compound responsible for ozone depletion and banned its use beginning in 1996.
[src:caffeine/1-1-1-trichloroethane] Since then, its manufacture and use have been phased out throughout most of the world, and its atmospheric concentration has declined substantially.
[src:caffeine/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] 3C-PEP is one of the most potent dopamine transporter (DAT) ligands reported to date.
[src:caffeine/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] It is highly selective for the dopamine transporter (dissociation constant Ki = 0.04 nM) with relatively low affinity for the closely related norepinephrine transporter (NET, Ki = 1107 nM ) and the serotonin transporter (SERT, Ki = 802 nM).
[src:caffeine/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] In addition, the compound has lower (or no) affinity for the PCP/NMDA receptor (Ki > 10000 nM), D2-like receptors (Ki = 327 nM), serotonin 5-HT2 receptors (Ki = 53 nM), and opioid receptors (Ki > 10000 nM).
[src:caffeine/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] With a DAT dissociation constant Ki of 0.04 nM, 3C-PEP is one of the most potent dopamine transporter ligands described to date in the literature.
[src:caffeine/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] In comparison, cocaine which is a prototypical DAT ligand and reuptake inhibitor has a dissociation constant Ki of 435 nm thus making 3C-PEP about 10,000 times more potent than cocaine as a dopamine transporter inhibitor *in vitro*.
[src:caffeine/1-3-chlorophenyl-4-2-phenylethyl-piperazine] 3C-PEP is not scheduled under the Controlled Drugs and Substances Act.
[src:caffeine/1-3-dimethylurea] 1,3-Dimethylurea is used for synthesis of caffeine, theophylline, pharmaceuticals, textile aids, herbicides and others.
[src:caffeine/1-3-dimethylurea] In the textile processing industry, 1,3-dimethylurea is used as intermediate for the production of formaldehyde-free easy-care finishing agents for textiles.
[src:caffeine/1-3-dimethylurea] The estimated world production of DMU is estimated to be less than 25,000 tons.
[src:caffeine/1-fluoro-18f-1-deoxyephedrine] It has high lipophilicity, allowing it to penetrate the blood-brain barrier without hindrance, which was accompanied by high, uniform uptake by the brain (approximately 8% of the administered dose), similar to that observed for the structurally related analogue [11C]methamphetamine.
[src:caffeine/1-fluoro-18f-1-deoxyephedrine] The ephedrine (1R,2S) isomer is three times more effective than the pseudoephedrine (1S,2S) isomer, it is a metabolically stable compound.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] It is a phenyltropane derivative that binds to the dopamine transporter with approximately 20 times the affinity of cocaine.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] However, it produces relatively mild stimulant effects, with a slow onset and a long duration of action.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] These characteristics make it a potential candidate for the treatment of cocaine addiction, as a possible substitute drug, analogous to the use of methadone for treating heroin dependence.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] RTI-336 fully substitutes for cocaine in addicted monkeys and supports self-administration, and significantly reduces rates of cocaine use, especially when combined with SSRIs.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] Research is ongoing to determine whether it could be a viable substitute drug in human cocaine addicts.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] RTI-336 and RTI-177 exhibited lower reinforcing strength than cocaine in nonhuman primates, indicating reduced abuse liability and supporting their viability as pharmacotherapies for addiction.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] Chronic RTI-336 administration in rhesus monkeys altered motor activity and sleep patterns but did not cause adverse hormonal changes, suggesting a relatively safe profile for long-term therapeutic use.
[src:caffeine/2β-3-4-methylphenyl-isoxazol-5-yl-3β-4-chlorophenyl-tropane] A dosage of up to 20mg has been tolerated in healthy males.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is a bitter, white crystalline purine, a methylxanthine alkaloid, and is chemically related to the adenine and guanine bases of deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA) and ribonucleic acid (RNA).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The most common sources of caffeine for human consumption are the tea leaves of the *Camellia sinensis* plant and the coffee bean, the seed of the *Coffea* plant.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some people drink beverages containing caffeine to relieve or prevent drowsiness and to improve cognitive performance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] To make these drinks, caffeine is extracted by steeping the plant product in water, a process called infusion.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine-containing drinks, such as tea, coffee, and cola, are consumed globally in high volumes.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In 2020, almost 10 million tonnes of coffee beans were consumed globally.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is the world's most widely consumed psychoactive drug.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Unlike most other psychoactive substances, caffeine remains largely unregulated and legal in nearly all parts of the world.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is seen as socially acceptable in most cultures and is encouraged in some.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine has both positive and negative health effects.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It can treat and prevent the premature infant breathing disorders bronchopulmonary dysplasia of prematurity and apnea of prematurity.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine citrate is on the WHO Model List of Essential Medicines.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It may confer a modest protective effect against some diseases, including Parkinson's disease.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can acutely improve reaction time and accuracy for cognitive tasks.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some people experience sleep disruption or anxiety if they consume caffeine, but others show little disturbance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Evidence of a risk during pregnancy is equivocal; some authorities recommend that pregnant women limit caffeine to the equivalent of two cups of coffee per day or less.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can produce a mild form of drug dependence – associated with withdrawal symptoms such as sleepiness, headache, and irritability – when an individual stops using caffeine after repeated daily intake.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Tolerance develops to autonomic effects (blood pressure, heart rate, nervousness) and to alerting/vigilance benefits with regular use.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Chronic exposure upregulates adenosine receptors, raising the effort threshold for allocating attention—even to mundane or previously enjoyable tasks—because habitual users operate from a lowered arousal baseline.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is classified by the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) as generally recognized as safe.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Lethal doses, over 10 grams per day for an adult, greatly exceed the typical dose of under 500 milligrams per day.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A 6 ounce cup of coffee typically contains 50–175 mg of caffeine, depending on what "bean" (seed) is used (and how much), how it is roasted, and how it is prepared (e.g., drip, percolation, or espresso).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Thus roughly 50–100 ordinary cups of coffee would be required to reach a lethal dose.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] However, pure powdered caffeine, which is available as a dietary supplement, can be lethal in tablespoon-sized amounts.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is used for both prevention and treatment of bronchopulmonary dysplasia in premature infants.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It may improve weight gain during therapy and reduce the incidence of cerebral palsy as well as reduce language and cognitive delay.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] On the other hand, subtle long-term side effects are possible.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is used as a primary treatment for apnea of prematurity, but not prevention.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is also used for orthostatic hypotension treatment.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some people use caffeine-containing beverages such as coffee or tea to try to treat their asthma.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Evidence to support this practice is poor.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It appears that caffeine in low doses improves airway function in people with asthma, increasing forced expiratory volume (FEV1) by 5% to 18% for up to four hours.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The addition of caffeine (100–130 mg) to commonly prescribed pain relievers such as paracetamol or ibuprofen modestly improves the proportion of people who achieve pain relief.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Consumption of caffeine after abdominal surgery shortens the time to recovery of normal bowel function and shortens length of hospital stay.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine was formerly used as a second-line treatment for attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is considered less effective than methylphenidate or amphetamine but more so than placebo for children with ADHD.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Children, adolescents, and adults with ADHD are more likely to consume caffeine, perhaps as a form of self-medication.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is a central nervous system stimulant that may reduce fatigue and drowsiness.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] At normal doses, caffeine has variable effects on learning and memory, but it generally improves reaction time, wakefulness, concentration, and motor coordination.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The amount of caffeine needed to produce these effects varies from person to person, depending on body size and degree of tolerance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The desired effects arise approximately one hour after consumption, and the desired effects of a moderate dose usually subside after about three or four hours.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can delay or prevent sleep and improves task performance during sleep deprivation.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Shift workers who use caffeine make fewer mistakes that could result from drowsiness.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine in a dose dependent manner increases alertness in both fatigued and normal individuals.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A systematic review and meta-analysis from 2014 found that concurrent caffeine and L-theanine use has synergistic psychoactive effects that promote alertness, attention, and task switching; these effects are most pronounced during the first hour post-dose.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A 2025 systematic review and meta-analysis found that acute caffeine intake can improve reaction time and accuracy for cognitive tasks.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Increased dosages can further improve reaction time but lead to decreases in accuracy after specific intake thresholds are reached.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is a proven ergogenic aid in humans.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine improves athletic performance in aerobic (especially endurance sports) and anaerobic conditions.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Moderate doses of caffeine (around 5 mg/kg) can improve sprint performance, cycling and running time trial performance, endurance (i.e., it delays the onset of muscle fatigue and central fatigue), and cycling power output.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine increases basal metabolic rate in adults.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine ingestion prior to aerobic exercise increases fat oxidation, particularly in persons with low physical fitness.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine improves muscular strength and power, and may enhance muscular endurance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine also enhances performance on anaerobic tests.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine consumption before constant load exercise is associated with reduced perceived exertion.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] While this effect is not present during exercise-to-exhaustion exercise, performance is significantly enhanced.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This is congruent with caffeine reducing perceived exertion, because exercise-to-exhaustion should end at the same point of fatigue.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine also improves power output and reduces time to completion in aerobic time trials, an effect positively (but not exclusively) associated with longer duration exercise.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] For the general population of healthy adults, Health Canada advises a daily intake of no more than 400 mg.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This limit was found to be safe by a 2017 systematic review on caffeine toxicology.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In healthy children, moderate caffeine intake under 400 mg produces effects that are "modest and typically innocuous".
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] As early as six months old, infants can metabolize caffeine at the same rate as that of adults.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Higher doses of caffeine (>400 mg) can cause physiological, psychological and behavioral harm, particularly for children with psychiatric or cardiac conditions.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] There is no evidence that coffee stunts a child's growth.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The American Academy of Pediatrics recommends that caffeine consumption, particularly in the case of energy and sports drinks, is not appropriate for children under the age of 18 and should be avoided.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] For children age 12 and under, Health Canada recommends a maximum daily caffeine intake of no more than 2.5 milligrams per kilogram of body weight.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Health Canada has not developed advice for adolescents because of insufficient data.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] However, they suggest that daily caffeine intake for this age group be no more than 2.5 mg/kg body weight.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This is because the maximum adult caffeine dose may not be appropriate for light-weight adolescents or for younger adolescents who are still growing.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The daily dose of 2.5 mg/kg body weight would not cause adverse health effects in the majority of adolescent caffeine consumers.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This is a conservative suggestion since older and heavier-weight adolescents may be able to consume adult doses of caffeine without experiencing adverse effects.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The metabolism of caffeine is reduced in pregnancy, especially in the third trimester, and the half-life of caffeine during pregnancy can be increased up to 15 hours (as compared to 2.5 to 4.5 hours in non-pregnant adults).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Evidence regarding the effects of caffeine on pregnancy and for breastfeeding are inconclusive.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] There is limited primary and secondary advice for, or against, caffeine use during pregnancy and its effects on the fetus or newborn.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The UK Food Standards Agency has recommended that pregnant women should limit their caffeine intake, out of prudence, to less than 200 mg of caffeine a day – the equivalent of two cups of instant coffee, or one and a half to two cups of fresh coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The American Congress of Obstetricians and Gynecologists (ACOG) concluded in 2010 that caffeine consumption is safe up to 200 mg per day in pregnant women.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] For women who breastfeed, are pregnant, or may become pregnant, Health Canada recommends a maximum daily caffeine intake of no more than 300 mg, or a little over two 8 oz (237 mL) cups of coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A 2017 systematic review on caffeine toxicology found evidence supporting that caffeine consumption up to 300 mg/day for pregnant women is generally not associated with adverse reproductive or developmental effect.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] There are conflicting reports in the scientific literature about caffeine use during pregnancy.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A 2011 review found that caffeine during pregnancy does not appear to increase the risk of congenital malformations, miscarriage or growth retardation even when consumed in moderate to high amounts.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Other reviews concluded that there is some evidence that higher caffeine intake by pregnant women may be associated with a higher risk of giving birth to a low birth weight baby, and may be associated with a higher risk of pregnancy loss.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A meta-analysis found a correlation between childhood obesity and maternal caffeine intake during pregnancy.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A systematic review analyzed the results of observational studies, and found that women who consumed large amounts of caffeine (greater than 300 mg/day) prior to becoming pregnant may have had a higher risk of experiencing pregnancy loss.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine in coffee and other caffeinated drinks can affect gastrointestinal motility and gastric acid secretion.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In postmenopausal women, high caffeine consumption can accelerate bone loss.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine, alongside other factors such as stress and fatigue, can also increase the pressure in various muscles, including the eyelids.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Acute ingestion of caffeine in large doses (at least 250–300 mg, equivalent to the amount found in 2–3 cups of coffee or 5–8 cups of tea) results in a short-term stimulation of urine output in individuals who have been deprived of caffeine for a period of days or weeks.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This increase is due to both a diuresis (increase in water excretion) and a natriuresis (increase in saline excretion); it is mediated via proximal tubular adenosine receptor blockade.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The acute increase in urinary output may increase the risk of dehydration.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] However, chronic users of caffeine develop a tolerance to this effect and experience no increase in urinary output.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Minor undesired symptoms from caffeine ingestion not sufficiently severe to warrant a psychiatric diagnosis are common and include mild anxiety, jitteriness, insomnia, increased sleep latency, and reduced coordination.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can have negative effects on anxiety disorders.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] According to a 2011 literature review, caffeine use may induce anxiety and panic disorders in people with Parkinson's disease.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] At high doses, typically greater than 300 to 400 mg caffeine can both cause and worsen anxiety.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] For some people, discontinuing caffeine use can significantly reduce anxiety.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In moderate doses, caffeine has been associated with reduced symptoms of depression and lower suicide risk.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Two reviews indicate that increased consumption of coffee and caffeine may reduce the risk of depression.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some sources state that caffeine is a mild euphoriant, while others state that it is not a euphoriant.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine-induced anxiety disorder is a subclass of the DSM-5 diagnosis of substance/medication-induced anxiety disorder.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Whether caffeine can result in an addictive disorder depends on how addiction is defined.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Compulsive caffeine consumption under any circumstances has not been observed, and caffeine is therefore not generally considered addictive.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some diagnostic sources, such as the ICD-9 and ICD-10, include a classification of caffeine addiction under a broader diagnostic model.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine does not appear to be a reinforcing stimulus, and some degree of aversion may actually occur, with people preferring placebo over caffeine in a study on drug abuse liability published in an NIDA research monograph.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some state that research does not provide support for an underlying biochemical mechanism for caffeine addiction.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Other research states it can affect the reward system.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] "Caffeine addiction" was added to the ICD-9 and ICD-10.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] However, its addition was contested with claims that this diagnostic model of caffeine addiction is not supported by evidence.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The American Psychiatric Association's DSM-5 does not include the diagnosis of a *caffeine addiction* but proposes criteria for the disorder for more study.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] As of 2021, the World Health Organization does not classify caffeine as an addictive substance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine withdrawal can cause mild to clinically significant distress or impairment in daily functioning.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The frequency at which this occurs is self-reported at 11%, but in lab tests only half of the people who report withdrawal actually experience it, casting doubt on many claims of dependence.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Mild physical dependence and withdrawal symptoms may occur upon abstinence, with greater than 100 mg caffeine per day, although these symptoms last no longer than a day.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some symptoms associated with psychological dependence may also occur during withdrawal.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The diagnostic criteria for caffeine withdrawal require a previous prolonged daily use of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Following 24 hours of a marked reduction in consumption, a minimum of 3 of these signs or symptoms is required to meet withdrawal criteria: difficulty concentrating (reflecting reversal of the neuroadapted state), depressed mood/irritability, flu-like symptoms, headache, and fatigue.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Additionally, the signs and symptoms must disrupt important areas of functioning and are not associated with effects of another condition.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The ICD-11 includes caffeine dependence as a distinct diagnostic category, which closely mirrors the DSM-5's proposed set of criteria for "caffeine-use disorder".
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine use disorder refers to dependence on caffeine characterized by failure to control caffeine consumption despite negative physiological consequences.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The APA, which published the DSM-5, acknowledged that there was sufficient evidence in order to create a diagnostic model of caffeine dependence for the DSM-5, but they noted that the clinical significance of the disorder is unclear.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Due to this inconclusive evidence on clinical significance, the DSM-5 classifies caffeine-use disorder as a "condition for further study".
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Tolerance to the effects of caffeine occurs for caffeine-induced elevations in blood pressure and the subjective feelings of nervousness though the effects are not drastic.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Sensitization, the process whereby effects become more prominent with use, may occur for positive effects such as feelings of alertness and wellbeing.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Tolerance varies for daily, regular caffeine users and high caffeine users.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] High doses of caffeine (750 to 1200 mg/day spread throughout the day) have been shown to produce complete tolerance to some, but not all of the effects of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Doses as low as 100 mg/day, such as a 6 oz (170 g) cup of coffee or two to three 12 oz (340 g) servings of caffeinated soft-drink, may continue to cause sleep disruption, among other intolerances.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Non-regular caffeine users have the least caffeine tolerance for sleep disruption.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some coffee drinkers develop tolerance to its undesired sleep-disrupting effects, but others apparently do not.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A neuroprotective effect of caffeine against Alzheimer's disease and dementia is possible but the evidence is inconclusive.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine may lessen the severity of acute mountain sickness if taken a few hours prior to attaining a high altitude.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] One meta analysis has found that caffeine consumption is associated with a reduced risk of type 2 diabetes.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Regular caffeine consumption may reduce the risk of developing Parkinson's disease and may slow the progression of Parkinson's disease.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine increases intraocular pressure in those with glaucoma but does not appear to affect normal individuals.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The DSM-5 also includes other caffeine-induced disorders consisting of caffeine-induced anxiety disorder, caffeine-induced sleep disorder and unspecified caffeine-related disorders.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The first two disorders are classified under "Anxiety Disorder" and "Sleep-Wake Disorder" because they share similar characteristics.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Other disorders that present with significant distress and impairment of daily functioning that warrant clinical attention but do not meet the criteria to be diagnosed under any specific disorders are listed under "Unspecified Caffeine-Related Disorders".
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is reputed to cause a fall in energy several hours after drinking, but this is not well researched.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine overdose can result in a state of central nervous system overstimulation known as caffeine intoxication, a clinically significant temporary condition that develops during, or shortly after, the consumption of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This syndrome typically occurs only after ingestion of large amounts of caffeine, well over the amounts found in typical caffeinated beverages and caffeine tablets (e.g., more than 400–500 mg at a time).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] High caffeine consumption in energy drinks (at least one liter or 320 mg of caffeine) was associated with short-term cardiovascular side effects including hypertension, prolonged QT interval, and heart palpitations.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] These cardiovascular side effects were not seen with smaller amounts of caffeine consumption in energy drinks (less than 200 mg).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] As of 2007 there is no known antidote or reversal agent for caffeine intoxication.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Treatment of mild caffeine intoxication is directed toward symptom relief; severe intoxication may require peritoneal dialysis, hemodialysis, or hemofiltration.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Intralipid infusion therapy is indicated in cases of imminent risk of cardiac arrest in order to scavenge the free serum caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Death from caffeine ingestion appears to be rare, and most commonly caused by an intentional overdose of medications.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In 2016, 3702 caffeine-related exposures were reported to Poison Control Centers in the United States, of which 846 required treatment at a medical facility, and 16 had a major outcome; and several caffeine-related deaths are reported in case studies.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The LD50 of caffeine in rats is 192 milligrams per kilogram of body mass.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The fatal dose in humans is estimated to be 150–200 milligrams per kilogram, which is 10.5–14 grams for a typical 70 kg (150 lb) adult, equivalent to about 75–100 cups of coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] There are cases where doses as low as 57 milligrams per kilogram have been fatal.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A number of fatalities have been caused by overdoses of readily available powdered caffeine supplements, for which the estimated lethal amount is less than a tablespoon.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The lethal dose is lower in individuals whose ability to metabolize caffeine is impaired due to genetics or chronic liver disease.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A death was reported in 2013 of a man with liver cirrhosis who overdosed on caffeinated mints.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is a substrate for CYP1A2, and interacts with many substances through this and other mechanisms.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] According to DSST, alcohol causes a decrease in performance on their standardized tests, and caffeine causes a significant improvement.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] When alcohol and caffeine are consumed jointly, the effects of the caffeine are changed, but the alcohol effects remain the same.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] For example, consuming additional caffeine does not reduce the effect of alcohol.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] However, the jitteriness and alertness given by caffeine is decreased when additional alcohol is consumed.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Alcohol consumption alone reduces both inhibitory and activational aspects of behavioral control.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine antagonizes the effect of alcohol on the activational aspect of behavioral control, but has no effect on the inhibitory behavioral control.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The Dietary Guidelines for Americans recommend avoidance of concomitant consumption of alcohol and caffeine, as taking them together may lead to increased alcohol consumption, with a higher risk of alcohol-associated injury.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Smoking tobacco has been shown to increase caffeine clearance by 56% as a result of polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons inducing the CYP1A2 enzyme.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The CYP1A2 enzyme that is induced by smoking is responsible for the metabolism of caffeine; increased enzyme activity leads to increased caffeine clearance, and is associated with greater coffee consumption for regular smokers.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Birth control pills can extend the half-life of caffeine by as much as 40%, requiring greater attention to caffeine consumption.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine sometimes increases the effectiveness of some medications, such as those for headaches.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine was determined to increase the potency of some over-the-counter analgesic medications by 40%.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The pharmacological effects of adenosine may be blunted in individuals taking large quantities of methylxanthines like caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some other examples of methylxanthines include the medications theophylline and aminophylline, which are prescribed to relieve symptoms of asthma or COPD.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In the absence of caffeine and when a person is awake and alert, little adenosine is present in CNS neurons.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] With a continued wakeful state, over time adenosine accumulates in the neuronal synapse, in turn binding to and activating adenosine receptors found on certain CNS neurons; when activated, these receptors produce a cellular response that ultimately increases drowsiness.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] When caffeine is consumed, it antagonizes adenosine receptors; in other words, caffeine prevents adenosine from activating the receptor by blocking the location on the receptor where adenosine binds to it.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] As a result, caffeine temporarily prevents or relieves drowsiness, and thus maintains or restores alertness.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is an antagonist of adenosine A2A receptors, and knockout mouse studies have specifically implicated antagonism of the A2A receptor as responsible for the wakefulness-promoting effects of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Antagonism of A2A receptors in the ventrolateral preoptic area (VLPO) reduces inhibitory GABA neurotransmission to the tuberomammillary nucleus, a histaminergic projection nucleus that activation-dependently promotes arousal.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This disinhibition of the tuberomammillary nucleus is the downstream mechanism by which caffeine produces wakefulness-promoting effects.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is an antagonist of all four adenosine receptor subtypes (A1, A2A, A2B, and A3), although with varying potencies.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The affinity (KD) values of caffeine for the human adenosine receptors are 12 μM at A1, 2.4 μM at A2A, 13 μM at A2B, and 80 μM at A3.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Antagonism of adenosine receptors by caffeine also stimulates the medullary vagal, vasomotor, and respiratory centers, which increases respiratory rate, reduces heart rate, and constricts blood vessels.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Adenosine receptor antagonism also promotes neurotransmitter release (e.g., monoamines and acetylcholine), which endows caffeine with its stimulant effects; adenosine acts as an inhibitory neurotransmitter that suppresses activity in the central nervous system.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Heart palpitations are caused by blockade of the A1 receptor.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Because caffeine is both water- and lipid-soluble, it readily crosses the blood–brain barrier that separates the bloodstream from the interior of the brain.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Once in the brain, the principal mode of action is as a nonselective antagonist of adenosine receptors (in other words, an agent that reduces the effects of adenosine).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The caffeine molecule is structurally similar to adenosine, and is capable of binding to adenosine receptors on the surface of cells without activating them, thereby acting as a competitive antagonist.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In addition to its activity at adenosine receptors, caffeine is an inositol trisphosphate receptor 1 antagonist and a voltage-independent activator of the ryanodine receptors (RYR1, RYR2, and RYR3).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is also a competitive antagonist of the ionotropic glycine receptor.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The A2A–D2 receptor heterotetramer has been identified as a primary pharmacological target of caffeine, primarily because it mediates some of its psychostimulant effects and its pharmacodynamic interactions with dopaminergic psychostimulants.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] During chronic caffeine use, caffeine-induced dopamine release within the nucleus accumbens core is markedly reduced due to drug tolerance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine, like other xanthines, also acts as a phosphodiesterase inhibitor.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] As a competitive nonselective phosphodiesterase inhibitor, caffeine raises intracellular cyclic AMP, activates protein kinase A, inhibits TNF-alpha and leukotriene synthesis, and reduces inflammation and innate immunity.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine also affects the cholinergic system where it is a moderate inhibitor of the enzyme acetylcholinesterase.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine from coffee or other beverages is absorbed by the small intestine within 45 minutes of ingestion and distributed throughout all bodily tissues.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Peak blood concentration is reached within 1–2 hours.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is eliminated by first-order kinetics.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can also be absorbed rectally, evidenced by suppositories of ergotamine tartrate and caffeine (for the relief of migraine) and of chlorobutanol and caffeine (for the treatment of hyperemesis).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] However, rectal absorption is less efficient than oral: the maximum concentration (Cmax) and total amount absorbed (AUC) are both about 30% (i.e., 1/3.5) of the oral amounts.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine's biological half-life – the time required for the body to eliminate one-half of a dose – varies widely among individuals according to factors such as pregnancy, other drugs, liver enzyme function level (needed for caffeine metabolism) and age.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In healthy adults, caffeine's half-life is between 3 and 7 hours.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The half-life is decreased by 30–50% in adult male smokers, approximately doubled in women taking oral contraceptives, and prolonged in the last trimester of pregnancy.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In newborns the half-life can be 80 hours or more, dropping rapidly with age, possibly to less than the adult value by age 6 months.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The antidepressant fluvoxamine (Luvox) reduces the clearance of caffeine by more than 90%, and increases its elimination half-life more than tenfold, from 4.9 hours to 56 hours.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] 1,3,7-Trimethyluric acid is a minor caffeine metabolite.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] 7-Methylxanthine is also a metabolite of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Each of the above metabolites is further metabolized and then excreted in the urine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can accumulate in individuals with severe liver disease, increasing its half-life.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A 2011 review found that increased caffeine intake was associated with a variation in two genes that increase the rate of caffeine catabolism.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Subjects who had this mutation on both chromosomes consumed 40 mg more caffeine per day than others.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This is presumably due to the need for a higher intake to achieve a comparable desired effect, not that the gene led to a disposition for greater incentive of habituation.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can be easily protonated by strong acids to form corresponding caffenium salts.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] They are of interest because these cations are one of the main species in an acidic medium.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Pure anhydrous caffeine is a bitter-tasting, white, odorless powder with a melting point of 235–238 °C.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is moderately soluble in water at room temperature (2 g/100 mL), but quickly soluble in boiling water (66 g/100 mL).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is also moderately soluble in ethanol (1.5 g/100 mL).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is weakly basic (pKa of conjugate acid = ~0.6) requiring strong acid to protonate it.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine does not contain any stereogenic centers and hence is classified as an achiral molecule.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The xanthine core of caffeine contains two fused rings, a pyrimidinedione and imidazole.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The pyrimidinedione in turn contains two amide functional groups that exist predominantly in a zwitterionic resonance the location from which the nitrogen atoms are double bonded to their adjacent amide carbons atoms.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Hence all six of the atoms within the pyrimidinedione ring system are sp2 hybridized and planar.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The imidazole ring also has a resonance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Therefore, the fused 5,6 ring core of caffeine contains a total of ten pi electrons and hence according to Hückel's rule is aromatic.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can be easily protonated to form corresponding caffeinium.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This cationic form is the main way in which caffeine exists in acidic solutions.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The biosynthesis of caffeine is an example of convergent evolution among different species.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine may be synthesized in the lab starting with 1,3-dimethylurea and malonic acid.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Industrially, caffeine is synthesized from urea and chloroacetic acid.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] A range of alternative processes are also possible.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Most processes for synthesizing caffeine are old, having been patented between the 1940s and the 1960s.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The synthesis of caffeine is inexpensive.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Germany, the birthplace of decaffeinated coffee, is home to several decaffeination plants, including the world's largest, Coffein Compagnie.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Over half of the decaf coffee sold in the US first travels from the tropics to Germany for caffeine removal before making its way to American consumers.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Coffee manufacturers recover the caffeine and resell it for use in soft drinks and over-the-counter caffeine tablets.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The efficiency and selectivity of caffeine removal depend on the decaffeination method used.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Water-based processes and supercritical carbon dioxide extraction are generally more selective, as they remove caffeine while preserving a larger proportion of volatile flavor compounds compared to some organic solvent methods.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Extraction of caffeine from coffee, to produce caffeine and decaffeinated coffee, can be performed using various solvents.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Decaffeination does not happen completely; some caffeine remains in the coffee beans.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some commercially available decaffeinated coffee products contain considerable levels.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] One study found that decaffeinated coffee contained 10 mg of caffeine per cup, compared to approximately 85 mg of caffeine per cup for regular coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine can be quantified in blood, plasma, or serum to monitor therapy in neonates, confirm a diagnosis of poisoning, or facilitate a medicolegal death investigation.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Plasma caffeine levels are usually in the range of 2–10 mg/L in coffee drinkers, 12–36 mg/L in neonates receiving treatment for apnea, and 40–400 mg/L in victims of acute overdosage.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Urinary caffeine concentration is frequently measured in competitive sports programs, for which a level in excess of 15 mg/L is usually considered to represent abuse.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Some analog substances have been created which mimic caffeine's properties with either function or structure or both.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Of the latter group are the xanthines DMPX and 8-chlorotheophylline, which is an ingredient in dramamine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Members of a class of nitrogen substituted xanthines are often proposed as potential alternatives to caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Many other xanthine analogues constituting the adenosine receptor antagonist class have also been elucidated.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine, as do other alkaloids such as cinchonine, quinine or strychnine, precipitates polyphenols and tannins.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This property can be used in a quantitation method.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The world's supply of pure (mostly anhydrous) caffeine for adding to drinks, pharmaceuticals, and other products comes from two sources: industrial synthesis and decaffeination of natural sources.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Despite the different production methods, the final products are chemically identical, as are their effects on the body.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Research on synthetic caffeine supports that it has the same stimulating effects on the body as natural caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Although many claim that natural caffeine is absorbed slower and therefore leads to a gentler caffeine crash, there is little scientific evidence supporting the notion.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Nevertheless, a demand for natural caffeine to satisfy consumer perception has grown so large that the decaffeinated product may be now considered a byproduct for the production of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] The global market exchanged 128,127 tons of anhydrous caffeine in 2022.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Most of the world's synthetic caffeine is produced by Chinese pharmaceutical companies, but an exact breakdown of supply between synthetic and natural does not seem to be available.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] It is possible to distinguish between natural and synthetic caffeine using carbon-13-to-carbon-12 isotope ratios, as most of the carbon from synthetic caffeine comes from petroleum sources with a more "ancient" carbon isotope signature.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Around thirty plant species are known to contain caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Common sources are the "beans" (seeds) of the two cultivated coffee plants, *Coffea arabica* and *Coffea canephora* (the quantity varies, but 1.3% is a typical value); and of the cocoa plant, *Theobroma cacao*; the leaves of the tea plant; and kola nuts.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Other sources include the leaves of yaupon holly, South American holly yerba mate, and Amazonian holly guayusa; and seeds from Amazonian maple guarana berries.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Temperate climates around the world have produced unrelated caffeine-containing plants.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine in plants acts as a natural pesticide: it can paralyze and kill predator insects feeding on the plant.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] High caffeine levels are found in coffee seedlings when they are developing foliage and lack mechanical protection.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] In addition, high caffeine levels are found in the surrounding soil of coffee seedlings, which inhibits seed germination of nearby coffee seedlings, thus giving seedlings with the highest caffeine levels fewer competitors for existing resources for survival.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine is stored in tea leaves in two places.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Firstly, in the cell vacuoles where it is complexed with polyphenols.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] This caffeine probably is released into the mouth parts of insects, to discourage herbivory.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Secondly, around the vascular bundles, where it probably inhibits pathogenic fungi from entering and colonizing the vascular bundles.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p01] Caffeine in nectar may improve the reproductive success of the pollen producing plants by enhancing the reward memory of pollinators, such as honey bees.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Products containing caffeine include coffee, tea, soft drinks ("colas"), energy drinks, other beverages, chocolate, caffeine tablets, other oral products, and inhalation products.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] According to a 2020 study in the United States, coffee is the major source of caffeine intake in middle-aged adults, while soft drinks and tea are the major sources in adolescents.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Energy drinks are more commonly consumed as a source of caffeine in adolescents as compared to adults.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The world's primary source of caffeine is the coffee "bean" (the seed of the coffee plant), from which coffee is brewed.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Caffeine content in coffee varies widely depending on the type of coffee bean and the method of preparation used; even beans within a given bush can show variations in concentration.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In general, one serving of coffee ranges from 80 to 100 milligrams, for a single shot (30 milliliters) of arabica-variety espresso, to approximately 100–125 milligrams for a cup (120 milliliters) of drip coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] *Arabica* coffee typically contains half the caffeine of the *robusta* variety.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In general, dark-roast coffee has slightly less caffeine than lighter roasts because the roasting process reduces caffeine content of the bean by a small amount.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Tea contains more caffeine than coffee by dry weight.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] A typical serving, however, contains much less, since less of the product is used as compared to an equivalent serving of coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Also contributing to caffeine content are growing conditions, processing techniques, and other variables.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Thus, teas contain varying amounts of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Tea contains small amounts of theobromine and slightly higher levels of theophylline than coffee.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Preparation and many other factors have a significant impact on tea, and color is a poor indicator of caffeine content.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Teas like the pale Japanese green tea, *gyokuro*, for example, contain far more caffeine than much darker teas like *lapsang souchong*, which has minimal caffeine content.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Caffeine is also a common ingredient of soft drinks, such as cola, originally prepared from kola nuts.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Soft drinks typically contain 0 to 55 milligrams of caffeine per 12 ounce (350 mL) serving.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] By contrast, energy drinks, such as Red Bull, can start at 80 milligrams of caffeine per serving.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The caffeine in these drinks either originates from the ingredients used or is an additive derived from the product of decaffeination or from chemical synthesis.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Guarana, a primary ingredient of energy drinks, contains large amounts of caffeine with small amounts of theobromine and theophylline in a naturally occurring slow-release excipient.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Defatted cocoa powder (14% fat) contain 230 mg caffeine per 100 g.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The caffeine content varies between cocoa bean strains.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The stimulant effect of chocolate may be due to a combination of theobromine and theophylline, as well as caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Tablets offer several advantages over coffee, tea, and other caffeinated beverages, including convenience, known dosage, and avoidance of concomitant intake of sugar or acids.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The use of caffeine in this form may increase alertness.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] These tablets are commonly used by students studying for their exams and by people who work or drive for long hours.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] One US company is marketing oral dissolvable caffeine strips.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Another intake route is SpazzStick, a caffeinated lip balm.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Alert Energy Caffeine Gum was introduced in the United States in 2013, but was voluntarily withdrawn after an announcement of an investigation by the FDA of the health effects of added caffeine in foods.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] There is weak evidence that the use of caffeine mouth washes might help cognitive performance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Similar to an e-cigarette, a caffeine inhaler may be used to deliver caffeine or a stimulant like guarana by vaping.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In 2012, the FDA sent a warning letter to one of the companies marketing an inhaler, expressing concerns for the lack of safety information available about inhaled caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] According to Chinese legend, the Chinese emperor Shennong, reputed to have reigned in about 3000 BCE, inadvertently discovered tea when he noted that when certain leaves fell into boiling water, a fragrant and restorative drink resulted.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Shennong is also mentioned in Lu Yu's *Cha Jing*, a famous early work on the subject of tea.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The earliest credible evidence of either coffee drinking or knowledge of the coffee plant appears in the middle of the fifteenth century, in the Sufi monasteries of the Yemen in southern Arabia.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] From Mokha, coffee spread to Egypt and North Africa, and by the 16th century, it had reached the rest of the Middle East, Persia and Turkey.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] From the Middle East, coffee drinking spread to Italy, then to the rest of Europe, and coffee plants were transported by the Dutch to the East Indies and to the Americas.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Kola nut use appears to have ancient origins.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] It is chewed in many West African cultures, in both private and social settings, to restore vitality and ease hunger pangs.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The earliest evidence of cocoa bean use comes from residue found in an ancient Mayan pot dated to 600 BCE.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Also, chocolate was consumed in a bitter and spicy drink called *xocolatl*, often seasoned with vanilla, chile pepper, and achiote.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] *Xocolatl* was believed to fight fatigue, a belief probably attributable to the theobromine and caffeine content.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Chocolate was an important luxury good throughout pre-Columbian Mesoamerica, and cocoa beans were often used as currency.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The leaves and stems of the yaupon holly (*Ilex vomitoria*) were used by Native Americans to brew a tea called *asi* or the "black drink".
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Archaeologists have found evidence of this use far into antiquity, possibly dating to Late Archaic times.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In 1819, the German chemist Friedlieb Ferdinand Runge isolated caffeine for the first time; he called it *"Kaffebase"* (i.e., a base that exists in coffee).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In 1821, caffeine was isolated both by the French chemist Pierre Jean Robiquet and by another pair of French chemists, Pierre-Joseph Pelletier and Joseph Bienaimé Caventou, according to Swedish chemist Jöns Jacob Berzelius in his yearly journal.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Furthermore, Berzelius stated that the French chemists had made their discoveries independently of any knowledge of Runge's or each other's work.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Pelletier's article on caffeine was the first to use the term in print (in the French form *Caféine* from the French word for coffee: **café**).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Robiquet was one of the first to isolate and describe the properties of pure caffeine, whereas Pelletier was the first to perform an elemental analysis.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Oudry isolated "théine" from tea, but in 1838 it was proved by Mulder and by Carl Jobst that theine was actually the same as caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In 1895, German chemist Hermann Emil Fischer (1852–1919) first synthesized caffeine from its chemical components (i.e. a "total synthesis"), and two years later, he also derived the structural formula of the compound.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] This was part of the work for which Fischer was awarded the Nobel Prize in 1902.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Because it was recognized that coffee contained some compound that acted as a stimulant, first coffee and later also caffeine has sometimes been subject to regulation.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] For example, in the 16th century Islamists in Mecca and in the Ottoman Empire made coffee illegal for some classes.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Charles II of England tried to ban it in 1676, Frederick II of Prussia banned it in 1777, and coffee was banned in Sweden at various times between 1756 and 1823.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In 1911, caffeine became the focus of one of the earliest documented health scares, when the US government seized 40 barrels and 20 kegs of Coca-Cola syrup in Chattanooga, Tennessee, alleging the caffeine in its drink was "injurious to health".
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Although the Supreme Court later ruled in favor of Coca-Cola in *United States v.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Forty Barrels and Twenty Kegs of Coca-Cola*, two bills were introduced to the US House of Representatives in 1912 to amend the Pure Food and Drug Act, adding caffeine to the list of "habit-forming" and "deleterious" substances, which must be listed on a product's label.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) considers safe beverages containing less than 0.02% caffeine; but caffeine powder, which is sold as a dietary supplement, is unregulated.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] It is a regulatory requirement that the label of most prepackaged foods must declare a list of ingredients, including food additives such as caffeine, in descending order of proportion.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] However, there is no regulatory provision for mandatory quantitative labeling of caffeine, (e.g., milligrams caffeine per stated serving size).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] There are a number of food ingredients that naturally contain caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] These ingredients must appear in food ingredient lists.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] However, as is the case for "food additive caffeine", there is no requirement to identify the quantitative amount of caffeine in composite foods containing ingredients that are natural sources of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] While coffee or chocolate are broadly recognized as caffeine sources, some ingredients (e.g., guarana, yerba maté) are likely less recognized as caffeine sources.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] For these natural sources of caffeine, there is no regulatory provision requiring that a food label identify the presence of caffeine nor state the amount of caffeine present in the food.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Global consumption of caffeine has been estimated at 120,000 tonnes per year, making it the world's most popular psychoactive substance.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The consumption of caffeine has remained stable between 1997 and 2015.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Coffee, tea and soft drinks are the most common caffeine sources, with energy drinks contributing little to the total caffeine intake across all age groups.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The Seventh-day Adventist Church asked for its members to "abstain from caffeinated drinks", but has removed this from baptismal vows (while still recommending abstention as policy).
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Some from these religions believe that one is not supposed to consume a non-medical, psychoactive substance, or believe that one is not supposed to consume a substance that is addictive.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints has said the following with regard to caffeinated beverages: "... the Church revelation spelling out health practices (Doctrine and Covenants 89) does not mention the use of caffeine.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Gaudiya Vaishnavas generally also abstain from caffeine, because they believe it clouds the mind and overstimulates the senses.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] To be initiated under a guru, one must have had no caffeine, alcohol, nicotine or other drugs, for at least a year.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Caffeinated beverages are widely consumed by Muslims.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] In the 16th century, some Muslim authorities made unsuccessful attempts to ban them as forbidden "intoxicating beverages" under Islamic dietary laws.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] The bacteria *Pseudomonas putida* CBB5 can live on pure caffeine and can cleave caffeine into carbon dioxide and ammonia.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Caffeine is toxic to birds and to dogs and cats, and has a pronounced adverse effect on mollusks, various insects, and spiders.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] This is at least partly due to a poor ability to metabolize the compound, causing higher levels for a given dose per unit weight.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Caffeine has also been found to enhance the reward memory of honey bees.
[src:caffeine/caffeine-p02] Caffeine has been used to double chromosomes in haploid wheat.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The nocaine family includes a diverse assortment of piperidine based cocaine mimetics.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The parent compound nocaine was developed in an attempt to create a substitute drug for cocaine for the treatment of addiction, and was found to substitute for cocaine in animal models while having significantly less abuse potential.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Although Kozikowski reported compound with chlorine in 1998, plain phenyl was reported earlier than this by John Plati.
[src:caffeine/cpca] There are several novel ways to produce these compounds, but background stems from arecoline chemistry.
[src:caffeine/cpca] This is analogous to the phenyltropanes which use Methylecgonidine.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Paroxetine (*Paxil*) and femoxetine were also developed using arecoline conjugate additions of aromatic moieties.
[src:caffeine/cpca] These are serotonin based antidepressants though, whereas Kozikowski's team was the first to highlight activity at the DAT.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Further nocaine derivatives were developed for treating addiction from Kozikowski's teachings.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Smith specifically states that the butyrophenone analog of nocaine is an active agent, as well as specifying pthalimide type alkylamino agents.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The Ketanserin analog devised by Peter Meltzer uses an altogether different methodology of synthesis: The same procedure was employed years earlier for GSK1360707F, and was known from before this from RTI diaryltropanes.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Thus, these methods are now well known in the art and do not necessarily rely on the use of arecoline as a starting material.
[src:caffeine/cpca] One of the more promising methods of synthesis relies on a protocol that was taken for paroxetine.
[src:caffeine/cpca] This is known as the Czibula procedure and was patented. {Note: can't go directly from syn alcohols to syn ethers due to rearrangement and therefore need tosyl group.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Another protocol is the pigs liver enzyme (PLE) protocol.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The method of improving the cited Ki by 3',4'-dichlorophenyl is now well known in the art and is heavily patented.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Like cocaine, (−)-cis-CPCA and (+)-CPCA bind to the dopamine transporter and inhibit dopamine uptake, stimulate motor activity in rodents and completely substitute for cocaine in discrimination tests.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Pretreatment with (−)-cis-CPCA or (+)-CPCA enhances the cocaine discriminative stimulus in rats.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The generally lower efficacy of (+)-CPCA in locomotor and methamphetamine discrimination tests could result from the differential selectivity of the two isomers for the DAT relative to the SERT.
[src:caffeine/cpca] That is, if serotonin receptor activation is requisite for maximal efficacy, the difference SERT affinity between (−)-cis-CPCA and (+)-CPCA might play a contributory role in accounting for the differences in the observed pharmacology.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Catecholamine selective drugs, like TMP (methylphenidate), are reported to possess decent abuse potential though, so it is not easy to gauge why (+)-CPCA does not entice a strong self-administration propensity.
[src:caffeine/cpca] A possible explanation might be nocaine preferentially binds to the ↓ DAT, in which case it would be expected to behave somewhat differently from cocaine.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Some sort of cholinergic effect might also be aversive.
[src:caffeine/cpca] For example, muscarinic activity of benztropine analogs is known to limit their reinforcing potential.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Ion-channel activity is another factor that can be used to explain certain differences in pharmacology.
[src:caffeine/cpca] It is possible that sigma receptor activity might also account for some of the differences between cocaine and these piperidine mimics (R.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Sigma receptors are not specific to cocaine, other psychostimulants like methylphenidate, methamphetamine (E.
[src:caffeine/cpca] 2005), and phencyclidine are also linked to this neural target.
[src:caffeine/cpca] An increased understanding of this receptor recently led to a novel AD being reported that is based around its pharmacology.
[src:caffeine/cpca] In summary, (+)-CPCA has lower potency and efficacy than cocaine in increasing locomotor activity in rodents.
[src:caffeine/cpca] (+)-CPCA only manages to produce partial methamphetamine-like discriminative stimulus effects, although it is fully cocaine-like in cocaine-trained animals.
[src:caffeine/cpca] (+)-CPCA has lower reinforcing potential than cocaine as assessed by fixed and progressive ratio IV self-administration tests in rats, with its reinforcing effects confirmed by rhesus monkeys.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Furthermore, (+)-CPCA dose dependently antagonizes cocaine-induced locomotion and potentiates the discriminative stimulus effects of a low dose of cocaine.
[src:caffeine/cpca] (+)-CPCA, unlike cocaine, does not enhance cocaine-induced convulsions.
[src:caffeine/cpca] These results suggest that (+)-CPCA completely mimics certain behavioral actions of cocaine, whereas acting like a weak partial agonist in others, including its ability to attenuate cocaine-induced increase in locomotion and to serve as a positive reinforcing agent in rodents.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Thus, (+)-CPCA may have potential utility in the treatment of cocaine addiction, and also offer valuable pharmacological information, furthering our understanding of cocaine's mechanism of action, because it exhibits fundamental differences from other related DARI molecules.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The arecoline route goes the same as for RTI-31 starting from Methylecgonidine.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Trudell lays down the groundwork for the correct procedure that was then heavily patented by SKF.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The temperature for forming the Grignard reagent needs to be reflux whereas the temperature needs to be refrigerated for the conjugate addition.
[src:caffeine/cpca] A catalytic amount of CuCl can encourage soft over hard addition.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Quench conditions (things like strength of acid used, quench temperature and time of quench).
[src:caffeine/cpca] A series of novel N- and 3α-modified nocaine analogs were synthesized and tested for their SNDRI activity and behavioral properties in mice.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The rational design of ligands with a predetermined potency at and selectivity for monoamine transporters is hindered by the lack of knowledge about the 3D structure of these targets.
[src:caffeine/cpca] In cases where the 3D structure of the binding site in a target protein is not well defined, as is the case for the monoamine transporter proteins, one can perform ligand-based design to develop a pharmacophore.
[src:caffeine/cpca] That is, by studying the conformational properties of a series of pharmacologically similar compounds, one can form hypotheses regarding the pharmacophore.
[src:caffeine/cpca] This model was successfully used for the design of a novel piperidine-based DAT inhibitor, that is economically affordable to manufacture.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Although the in vivo metabolism of (+)-CPCA is also likely to involve N-demethylation, metabolism to the corresponding free acid, to give a compound inactive at all monoamine transporters, will probably be the predominant pathway *in vivo*.
[src:caffeine/cpca] It was reasoned that metabolism via esterase action can be avoided by replacing the ester group with a bioisosteric group that is more stable to metabolic degradation.
[src:caffeine/cpca] In previous studies, it was found that oxadiazole, although cocaine-like in activity, exhibits a significantly longer duration of action due to slower rate of metabolism.
[src:caffeine/cpca] In general, relative to the corresponding N-methyl compounds, the norpiperidines exhibited an increased activity at the SERT/NET and only modest changes at the DAT.
[src:caffeine/cpca] An interesting difference between cocaine, ester **1a**, alcohol **2a**, and norester **1b** is that the latter two compounds are substantially longer acting than cocaine in locomotor activity tests in mice.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Another result of N-demethylation is an initial depressant action of **1b** followed by delayed locomotor stimulation, which might be due to interaction with GABA receptors or mGlu5.
[src:caffeine/cpca] In an earlier study, it was found that 3α-amido and bulky 3α-oxadiazoyl nocaine ligands, which possess greater stability relative to the ester functional group, and are therefore more attractive as potential therapies, are inactive.
[src:caffeine/cpca] This result led to the hypothesis that the binding site of the DAT and NET in close proximity to the 3α-position of the piperidine ring is compact and cannot accommodate bulky, sterically occluded substituents, like the 3-substituted 1,2,4-oxadiazolyl groups.
[src:caffeine/cpca] It was reasoned that introduction of a methylene spacer would confer improved monoamine transporter binding affinity upon the resultant molecules.
[src:caffeine/cpca] One of the possible reasons that the C2–C3 compounds are more active than the C1 compounds is that the polar group present in the more flexible 3α-appendage of the C2–C3 ligands is able to avoid unfavorable interactions with the binding site in close proximity to the piperidine ring.
[src:caffeine/cpca] For the same reason the appendage in the C2–C3 series may more closely, but not precisely, mimic the binding mode of the more active *SS* based ligands, and possibly even transfer over to tropane based compounds.
[src:caffeine/cpca] To better understand the difference between the C1 and the C2–C3 series, the compounds were energy minimized and flexibly superimposed on WIN-35,428.
[src:caffeine/cpca] The resulting overlay shows that only the C2–C3 ligands are able to adopt a conformation in which the polar group of the 3α-substituent occupies the position proximal to that of the 2β-polar group in WIN35428.
[src:caffeine/cpca] A generally recognized pharmacophore model for cocaine and phenyltropanes comprises two electrostatic interactions of the basic nitrogen and the ester group of the C-2 substituent, and one hydrophobic interaction of the C-3 aryl group.
[src:caffeine/cpca] This model has been disputed because of the finding that in certain compounds neither the basic N nor the ester group was necessary for high binding affinity and inhibition of MAR.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Instead, a hydrophobic pocket was proposed to exist in the vicinity of the C-2 carbon.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Carroll et al., however, provided further evidence for an electrostatic interaction at the C-2β-position in a later study.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Other models proposed for the DAT binding site include a linear fashion binding pocket for the 3β-substituted phenyltropane analogs, and a prohibited conical region about 5.5–10 Å distant from the 3α-substituted piperidine ring.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Noticeably, high potency at the DAT of dimeric piperidine-based esters and amides suggested that the flexible linker combining the two piperidine units was able to adjust its orientation and to avoid unfavorable interactions with the binding site.
[src:caffeine/cpca] All these lines of evidence suggest that the DAT binding site is much more complicated than the proposed pharmacophore models.
[src:caffeine/cpca] In an attempt to uncover the details of the DAT binding site, a number of 3D-QSAR studies were performed.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Several QSAR/CoMFA studies focused on phenyltropanes concluded that an increased negative electrostatic potential in the regions around the 3β-substituent of the tropane ring and the para-position of the phenyl ring favored high potency in inhibiting the MATs.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Wright et al. studied the role of the 3β-substituent of tropanes in binding to the DAT and blocking DA re-uptake.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Their CoMFA model indicated that the 3β-substituent binding site is **barrel-shaped** and hydrophobic interactions make a dominant contribution to the binding, which is consistent with the studies of 3α-substituted tropane analogs reported by Newman et al.
[src:caffeine/cpca] Newman and co-authors also studied N-substituted tropanes and concluded that the steric interaction of the N-substituent with the DAT is a principal factor for the binding affinity.
